Mechanical role of Type I myosin in CME theory project

recent progress

  • got help from research IT to fix issues with computing clusters; high-throughput simulations are running smoothly now
  • did parameter sensitivity analysis to constrain things we don't have direct experimental data for (for supplemental figure)

    • myosin motor stepping stall force: seems unimportant

    • myosin head group distance from membrane: unimportant

    • myosin bond stiffness (spring constant): threshold engagement of catch bond at high stiffness

    • myosin binding range (distance from head group to actin filament in which binding is possible): catch bond is sensitive to full range, need to just pick a value

  • using reviewer comments from Ross's manuscript to further hone the biological question for this project: what is the mechanism of type I myosin's assistance to CME from the perspective of actin organization?

  • currently working out analysis methods to extract the readouts we need for putting together the story

    • actin density, filament count, capped vs. uncapped end count

    • comparison of internalization in different myosin property combinations to the total actin density

    • analyis of per-filament elongation rate TBD
  • set up standing weekly meetings with Ross and Matt to keep things moving quickly

Hip1r catch bond theory collaboration

  • ran a pilot parameter sweep of Hip1r properties; as we expected there is a predicted effect of the catch bond on CME internalization
  • Leanna is writing up a mini-proposal based on these results and her conceptual model of Hip1r biology
  • initiated training Leanna on cytosim and the computing cluster so she can eventually run her own simulations

Nikhil's protein purification project

  • very informative meeting with Eileen Lafer and Liping Wang for IDR protein purification troubleshooting
  • we received extremely detailed protocols and gels for Eps15 and Fcho1 that Nikhil will carefully reproduce starting this week (new reagents just arrived today: Ni-NTA agarose resin, thrombin cleavage kit, spin desalting columns)
  • One big equipment difference: they use this "stain-free imaging system" for SDS-PAGE gels because minimizing waiting time is essential to minimize degradation of these proteins and it's also a quantitative measurement of protein concentration. They have a different gel imager but we will check if it's compatible with the 5th floor imager…
